Being an introverted creative and working independently while placing great value on one's privacy should not be a contradiction — but it often is. Most online sources and coaches advise working with the (evil) tech giants and acting extroverted. Advertise here, follow the algorithm, show your personality. Get that blue checkmark on that service, be reachable 24/7, respond to inquiries with a video of yourself, reply immediately. Video, video, video.
1/3
For me, it is a year of changes.
I don't want to feed the tech giants with money, data, and my own energy. Or coaches who have their own extroverted solutions and just push them onto everyone. I'm looking for new ways to run a business, while at the same time fighting against my long-held belief that there's a specific way you have to do things in order to be successful.
Wish me luck!
I have already taken the first steps.
I have canceled my FB account, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
Yesterday I also removed Google Analytics, the last external tracker, from my website and feel good about it.
Recently, I subscribed to a European CRM to have better DSGVO support, and I will be moving my business there in the next few weeks.
I transferred my MX account to Proton and now have full SPF, DKIM, and DMARC, without having to pay Google for regular email validation.
3/3
